text: i spoke at Devoxx Morocco 2024..  ğ—¯ğ˜‚ğ˜ ğ˜ğ—µğ—¶ğ˜€ ğ˜ğ—¶ğ—ºğ—² -- ğ—¶ ğ—¹ğ—¶ğ˜ƒğ—²ğ—± ğ˜ğ—µğ—² ğ—™ğ—¨ğ—Ÿğ—Ÿ ğ—²ğ˜…ğ—½ğ—²ğ—¿ğ—¶ğ—²ğ—»ğ—°ğ—²!  let me tell you how different it was..  last year  I could only attend the last day due to exams.  and this year  kant myssra hamdulillah!  what an experience it was...   from day one to day three  every moment was precious.  the rooms were packed  the energy was unmatched  and the community?   any words i d use to describe would be nothing compared to what i m really feeling!   i reconnected with the amazing people I met last year   and made even more connections    even though some of my cool folks couldn t join unfortunately..  (hanya khirha f ghirha)  the lounge discussions.. the lunch debates.. the post-conference with tanjia..  everything was unexpected yet perfect!  having the full three days made such a difference:  we got more networking opportunities. more high-quality and fun sessions to attend. more time to digest and discuss ideas.  as a student who will graduate soon  i actually learned a lot!  and i m so grateful and thankful for the cool and humble friends i met.  thank you  Devoxx Morocco  for another unforgettable year.  thank you for helping us all grow.  see you in 2025  inshallah! ğŸ™  ğŸ“·: Dimitris Doutsiopoulos

This World Mental Health Day  we call for urgent action to address the mental health needs of children in Gaza.  We are staring down the lens of a mental health pandemic amongst children in Gaza.  The escalating violence in Gaza has intensified a mental health crisis among its 2Â·1 million residents  of whom 47% are younger than 18 years.  The last 12 months of constant bombardment and displacement and the loss of family members are leaving many children exposed to anxiety  depression  post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD)  and other adverse mental health conditions.   We urge governments  organisations  and individuals to advocate for increased mental health resources and services in the Gaza Strip. This includes access to therapy  trauma-informed care  and community support programmes that can help children process their experiences and begin to heal.  Mental health support is not just an afterthought; it must be recognised as a critical component of humanitarian aid and support for the children of Gaza and we are working on initiatives and strategising efforts to respond to this overwhelming need.  ğŸ¥ @yaqob.salama

text: Being part of a community that shares the love for Orisha music is a unique and irreplaceable experience. Singing these sacred songs in harmony with others reminds me of the deep strength we draw from tradition and how music becomes a bridge that connects us across time and distance. Every note  every rhythm  every voice joined together carries the spirit of those who came before us and those who walk beside us.  I deeply miss performing with the London Lucumi Choir and the shared energy that brought each song to life! Grateful for the opportunity to carry this music forward and for the support from Calgary Arts Development and Tropical Pressure Festival that made it all possible. Thank you to Daniela de Armas and the entire London Lucumi Choir for creating such a powerful  soulful space. More memories to share soon! âœ¨  Song: Sequence for Yemaya (Iworere) by the London Lucumi Choir (@londonlucumichoir)  Location: Cornwall  U.K Photo credit: Rebecca Radmore (@firesoulmedia)  #LondonLucumiChoir #Orishas #Lucumi #AfroCuban #Africandiaspora #cubanmusic #london #cornwall #calgaryarts #yycartist #calgaryartist

text: 2024 Burning Man â€œCURIOUSER AND CURIOUSERâ€â€¦ I wanted the words to be simple but what flows will flow:  The curious thing was  before I decided to go this year literally 5 days before the burn  I was told by a medium to keep dreaming  for that was literally my gift. â€œYou are the visionary she said and through you the divine speaks.â€ She gave a light chuckle as if I was silly for thinking anything but. When we release our tight grip on our identities  understanding that what we cling to is also what we seek so desperately to transform  Humanity will know peace. text: You need to know what Iâ€™m about to share  because itâ€™s the  unspoken truth every designer faces:    The Fear of When Design Goes Wrong.  We all dream of creating stunning  impactful designs   but lurking beneath the surface are anxieties that can cripple our creativity.  Â  Let s shine a light on these fears and how to conquer them:   The Designer s Biggest Fears:  The Fear of Failure: That sinking feeling that your work won t measure up  that you ll fall short of expectations. But remember  failure is a stepping stone to growth.    The Fear of Criticism: It s tough to put your heart into something only to have it critiqued. But constructive feedback is gold. Learn to separate personal feelings from professional insights.    The Fear of Being Replaced : The design landscape is a whirlwind of new tools and trends. It s easy to feel overwhelmed. But instead of fearing change  embrace it. Stay curious  continuously learn  and adapt.   The Fear of Losing Inspiration: The creative well can run dry.  It happens to the best of us. Don t panic.
